bleSeeder.php in your text editor and add the below code in run method.</p>\r\n[php]\r\n	DB::table(\'subjects\')-&gt;insert([\r\n		\'name\' =&gt; \'Java\',\r\n		\'author\' =&gt; \'James Gosling\',\r\n		\'created_at\' =&gt; date(&quot;Y-m-d H:i:s&quot;)\r\n	]);\r\n[/php]\r\n<p>By default, Laravel provides a DatabaseSeeder class. Using this class, we can use the call method to run other seed classes, allowing you to control the seeding order. Open the DatabaseSeeder.php in your text editor and add the below code in run method.</p>\r\n[php]\r\n   $this-&gt;call(SubjectsTableSeeder::class);\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>To run the seeds, execute the below code in your command prompt or terminal</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n   php artisan db:seed\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/laravel_seeder_command.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Seeder Command\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/laravel_seeder_insert_db.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Seeder Insert\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\'shr\'>That\'s it!. Please share your thoughts or suggestions in the comments below.</p>','How to use Laravel Database Seeding?','','publish','open','open','','how-to-use-laravel-database-seeding','','','2019-09-10 07:44:35','2019-09-10 02:14:35','',0,'https://nexladder.com/blog/?p=61',0,'post','',7),(62,1,'2018-09-02 06:52:48','2018-09-02 01:22:48','In this article, We\'ll see how to use Laravel Database Seeding? Seed allows you to insert data into your database. We can use the <code>query builder</code> to manually insert data or <code>Eloquent model factories</code>.\r\n\r\nTo generate a seeder, execute the <code>make:seeder</code> Artisan command. All seeders will be placed in your <code>database/seeds</code> directory.\r\n\r\nLet\'s assume we have table \'subjects\' in the database. This table contains the columns name, author etc.\r\n\r\nOpen the command prompt or terminal in your Laravel project. To use the seed, we create a seeder wh