</code> Artisan command. All seeders will be placed in your <code>database/seeds</code> directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let\'s assume we have table \'subjects\' in the database. This table contains the columns name, author etc.</p>\r\n<p>Open the command prompt or terminal in your Laravel project. To use the seed, we create a seeder which insert the data in table \'subjects\'.</p>\r\n[php]\r\n  php artisan make:seeder SubjectsTableSeeder\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/laravel_seeder.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Seeder\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"text-center\"><script async src=\"//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js\"></script><br />\r\n<!-- Ad 4 --><br />\r\n<ins class=\"adsbygoogle\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 300px; height: 250px;\" data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-9716398444039739\" data-ad-slot=\"4680411731\"></ins><br />\r\n<script>\r\n                          (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});\r\n                          </script>\r\n</p>						  \r\n\r\n<p>A seeder class only contains one method by default: <code>run</code>. This method is called when the <code>db:seed</code> Artisan command is executed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the SubjectsTableSeeder.php in your text editor and add the below code in run method.</p>\r\n[php]\r\n	DB::table(\'subjects\')-&gt;insert([\r\n		\'name\' =&gt; \'Java\',\r\n		\'author\' =&gt; \'James Gosling\',\r\n		\'created_at\' =&gt; date(&quot;Y-m-d H:i:s&quot;)\r\n	]);\r\n[/php]\r\n<p>By default, Laravel provides a DatabaseSeeder class. Using this class, we can use the call method to run other seed classes, allowing you to control the seeding order. Open the DatabaseSeeder.php in your text editor and add the below code in run method.</p>\r\n[php]\r\n   $this-&gt;call(SubjectsTableSeeder::class);\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>To run the seeds, execute the below code in your command prompt or terminal</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n   php artisan db:seed\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/laravel_seeder_command.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Seeder Command\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/laravel_seeder_insert_db.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Seeder Insert\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\'shr\'>That\'s it!. Please share your thoughts or suggestions in the comments below.</p>','How to use Laravel Database Seeding?','','inherit','closed','closed','','61-revision-v1','','','2019-09-10 07:44:35','2019-09-10 02:14:35','',61,'https://nexladder.com/blog/61-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(288,1,'2019-09-11 06:08:10','2019-09-11 00:38:10','<p>In this article, We\'ll see how to use Laravel Tinker? Tinker allows you to interact with your entire Laravel application on the command line, including the Eloquent ORM, jobs, events, and more.<p>\n\n<p>Tinker is the Laravel\'s built-in feature, We don\'t need to install them separately.<p>\n\n<p>Let\'s create a table i.e \'subjects\' in the database using migration. This table contains the columns i.e id, name, author etc.<p>\n\n<p>To create a migration, use the <code>make:migration</code> artisan command:<p>\n\n[php]\n  php artisan make:migration create_subjects_table\n[/php]\n\n<p>The migration will be placed in your <code>database/migrations</code> directory.<p>\n\n<p>Open the xxxx_xx_xx_xxxxxx_create_subjects_table.php in your text editor and add the below two line in create method on the <code>Schema</code> facade.<p>\n\n[php]\n  $table-&gt;string(\'name\')-&gt;comment(\'Subject\');\n  $table-&gt;string(\'author\')-&gt;comment(\'Author\');\n[/php]\n\n<p>To run migration, run the below artisan command:<p>\n\n[php]\n   php artisan migrate\n[/php]\n\n<p>this migration creates a subjects table.<p>\n<p class=\"text-center\"><script async src=\"//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js\"></script>\n<!-- Ad 4 -->\n<ins class=\"adsbygoogle\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 300px; height: 250px;\" data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-9716398444039739\" data-ad-slot=\"4680411731\"></ins>\n<script>\n                          (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});\n                          </script></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_migrate_tables.jpg\" alt=\"\" /><p>\n\n<p>Now we\'ll insert a row in the \'subjects\' table using the Laravel Tinker.<p>\n\n<p>Open the command prompt or terminal in your Laravel project. To use the tinker, we create a model which interacts with the table \'subjects\'.</p>\n\n<p>Below command create a model i.e \'Subject.php\' under the \'app\' directory.</p>\n\n[php]\n   php artisan make:model Subject\n[/php]\n\nNext, run the below command.\n\n[php]\n   php artisan tinker\n[/php]\n\n<p>We use the Eloquent ORM to insert a row in our database\'s table \'subjects\'.</p>\n\n[php]\n  $subject = new App\\Subject;\n  $subject-&gt;name = \'Laravel\';\n  $subject-&gt;author = \'Taylor Otwell\';\n  $subject-&gt;save();\n[/php]\n\n<p>Write the above code in command-line.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_insert.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_subjects_table_insert.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n\n<p>To update the record, we write the below code in a command-line.</p>\n\n[php]\n  $subject = App\\Subject::find(1); // Retrieve a model by its primary key...\n  $subject-&gt;name = \'CodeIgniter\';\n  $subject-&gt;author = \'EllisLab\';\n  $subject-&gt;save();\n[/php]\n\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_update.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_subjects_table_update.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n\n<p>To delete the record, we write the below code in a command-line.</p>\n\n[php]\n$subject = App\\Subject::find(1); // Retrieve a model by its primary key...\n$subject-&gt;delete();\n[/php]\n\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_delete.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n\n<p class=\'shr\'>That\'s it!. Please share your thoughts or suggestions in the comments below.</p>','How to use Laravel Tinker?','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-autosave-v1','','','2019-09-11 06:08:10','2019-09-11 00:38:10','',49,'https://nexladder.com/blog/49-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(289,1,'2019-09-11 06:09:37','2019-09-11 00:39:37','<p>In this article, We\'ll see how to use Laravel Tinker? Tinker allows you to interact with your entire Laravel application on the command line, including the Eloquent ORM, jobs, events, and more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tinker is the Laravel\'s built-in feature, We don\'t need to install them separately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let\'s create a table i.e \'subjects\' in the database using migration. This table contains the columns i.e id, name, author etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To create a migration, use the <code>make:migration</code> artisan command:</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n  php artisan make:migration create_subjects_table\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>The migration will be placed in your <code>database/migrations</code> directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the xxxx_xx_xx_xxxxxx_create_subjects_table.php in your text editor and add the below two line in create method on the <code>Schema</code> facade.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n  $table-&gt;string(\'name\')-&gt;comment(\'Subject\');\r\n  $table-&gt;string(\'author\')-&gt;comment(\'Author\');\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>To run migration, run the below artisan command:</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n   php artisan migrate\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>this migration creates a subjects table.</p>\r\n<p class=\"text-center\"><script async src=\"//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js\"></script>\r\n<!-- Ad 4 -->\r\n<ins class=\"adsbygoogle\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 300px; height: 250px;\" data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-9716398444039739\" data-ad-slot=\"4680411731\"></ins>\r\n<script>\r\n                          (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});\r\n                          </script></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_migrate_tables.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now we\'ll insert a row in the \'subjects\' table using the Laravel Tinker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open the command prompt or terminal in your Laravel project. To use the tinker, we create a model which interacts with the table \'subjects\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below command create a model i.e \'Subject.php\' under the \'app\' directory.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n   php artisan make:model Subject\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>Next, run the below command.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n   php artisan tinker\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>We use the Eloquent ORM to insert a row in our database\'s table \'subjects\'.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n  $subject = new App\\Subject;\r\n  $subject-&gt;name = \'Laravel\';\r\n  $subject-&gt;author = \'Taylor Otwell\';\r\n  $subject-&gt;save();\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p>Write the above code in command-line.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_insert.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_subjects_table_insert.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To update the record, we write the below code in a command-line.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n  $subject = App\\Subject::find(1); // Retrieve a model by its primary key...\r\n  $subject-&gt;name = \'CodeIgniter\';\r\n  $subject-&gt;author = \'EllisLab\';\r\n  $subject-&gt;save();\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_update.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_subjects_table_update.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To delete the record, we write the below code in a command-line.</p>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n$subject = App\\Subject::find(1); // Retrieve a model by its primary key...\r\n$subject-&gt;delete();\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://nexladder.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/laravel_artisan_delete.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\'shr\'>That\'s it!. Please share your thoughts or suggestions in the comments below.</p>','How to use Laravel Tinker?','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2019-09-11 06:09:37','2019-09-11 00:39:37','',49,'https://nexladder.com/blog/49-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(290,1,'2019-09-11 06:12:12','2019-09-11 00:42:12','<p>In this article, we\'ll see about what does <code>int(11)</code> means in MySQL. most of the developer think that int(11) means in MySQL is that the int column can store maximum integer value with 11 digits in length. However, this is not true. in int(11), 11 is the <strong>display width</strong> of the integer column, unlike the characters columns where the number means number of character that can be stored.</p>\n\n<p><code>int(11)</code> - The number in the parenthesis i.e <strong>()</strong> does not determines the max and min values that can be stored in the integer field. The max and min values that can be stored are always fixed. It is just <strong>display width</strong> of integer data type.</p>\n\n<p class=\"text-center\">\n<script async src=\"//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js\"></script>\n<!-- Ad 4 -->\n<ins class=\"adsbygoogle\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 300px; height: 250px;\" data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-9716398444039739\" data-ad-slot=\"4680411731\"></ins>\n<script>\n                          (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});\n                          </script>\n</p>\n\n<p>The number in the bracket in <strong>int(N)</strong> is often confused by the maximum size allowed for the column, as it does in the case of <strong>varchar(N)</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>But this is not the case with Integer data types- the number N in the bracket is not the maximum size for the column, but simply a parameter to tell MySQL what width to display the column at when the table\'s data is being viewed via the MySQL console (when you\'re using the ZEROFILL attribute).</p>\n\n<p>Below the required storage and range for each integer type.</p>\n\n<p>An INT will always be 4 bytes no matter what length is specified.</p>\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>TINYINT</strong> = 1 byte (8 bit)</li>\n 	<li><strong>SMALLINT</strong> = 2 bytes (16 bit)</li>\n 	<li><strong>MEDIUMINT</strong> = 3 bytes (24 bit)</li>\n 	<li><strong>INT</strong> = 4 bytes (32 bit)</li>\n 	<li><strong>BIGINT</strong> = 8 bytes (64 bit)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Above, We\'ve seen that MySQL integer <strong>int(11)</strong> has size is <strong>4</strong> bytes which equals <strong>32 bit</strong>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Signed value is </strong>: <code>-2^(32-1) to 0 to 2^(32-1)-1</code> = <code>-2147483648 to 0 to 2147483647</code>. One bit is for sign.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Unsigned values is </strong>: <code>0 to 2^32-1</code> = <code>0 to 4294967295</code></p>\n\n<p>INT(num) will make difference only in term of display, that is to show in the number in \'num\' digits, and not restricted only to 11. You pair it using ZEROFILL, which will prepend the zeros until it matches your length.</p>\n\n<p>Remarks :</p>\n\n<p>if the value has less digit than \'num\', <strong>ZEROFILL</strong> will prepend zeros.</p>\n<ul>\n 	<li>INT(5) ZEROFILL with the stored value of 32 will show 00032</li>\n 	<li>INT(5) with the stored value of 32 will show 32</li>\n 	<li>INT with the stored value of 32 will show 32</li>\n</ul>\n<p>if the value has more digit than \'num\', the stored value will be shown.</p>\n<ul>\n 	<li>INT(3) ZEROFILL with the stored value of 150000 will show 150000</li>\n 	<li>INT(3) with the stored value of 150000 will show 150000</li>\n 	<li>INT with the stored value of 150000 will show 150000</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The similar applies to BIGINT, MEDIUMINT, SMALLINT, and TINYINT as well.</p>\n\n<p>The number in brackets will tell MySQL how many zeros to pad incoming integers with. For example: If you\'re using ZEROFILL on a column that is set to INT(5) and the number 78 is inserted, MySQL will pad that value with zeros until the number satisfies the number in brackets. i.e. 78 will become 00078 and 127 will become 00127. To sum it up: The number in brackets is used for display purposes.</p>\n\n<p>In a way, the number in brackets is kind of useless unless you\'re using the ZEROFILL attribute.</p>\n\n<p>Here is an example of how this the display value affect the columns which are ZEROFILL.</p>\n\n[php]\n     CREATE TABLE `tbl_zerofill` (\n       `id` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,\n       `int1` int(10) NOT NULL,\n       `int2` int(3) NOT NULL,\n       `zerofill1` int(10) ZEROFILL NOT NULL,\n       `zerofill2` int(3) ZEROFILL NOT NULL,\n       PRIMARY KEY (`id`)\n      ) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8;\n[/php]\n\n\n[php]\n   INSERT INTO `tbl_zerofill` (`int1`, `int2`, `zerofill1`, `zerofill2`) VALUES (10000, 10000, 10000, 10000), (100, 100, 100, 100);\n[/php]\n\n\n[php]\n  SELECT * FROM `tbl_zerofill`;\n[/php]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>+----+-------+-------+------------+-----------+\n| id | int1  | int2  | zerofill1  | zerofill2 |\n+----+-------+-------+------------+-----------+\n|  1 | 10000 | 10000 | 0000010000 |     10000 |\n|  2 |   100 |   100 | 0000000100 |       100 |\n+----+-------+-------+------------+-----------+\n</pre>\n<p class=\'shr\'>That\'s it!. Please share your thoughts or suggestions in the comments below.</p>','What does int(11) means in MySQL?','','inherit','closed','closed','','39-autosave-v1','','','2019-09-11 06:12:12','2019-09-11 00:42:12','',39,'https://nexladder.com/blog/39-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(291,1,'2019-09-11 06:12:31','2019-09-11 00:42:31','<p>In this article, we\'ll see about what does <code>int(11)</code> means in MySQL. most of the developer think that int(11) means in MySQL is that the int column can store maximum integer value with 11 digits in length. However, this is not true. in int(11), 11 is t